'''''Magnolia liliifera''''', commonly known as '''egg magnolia''', is a flowering tree native to the [[Indomalaya ecozone]].<ref name=GRIN>{{GRIN | name = ''Magnolia liliifera''  (L.) Baill. | id = 411208 | accessdate = April 23, 2014}}</ref><ref name=IUCN>{{IUCN | id = 39004 | taxon = Magnolia liliifera | assessor = Chua, L.S.L. | assessment_year = 1998 | version = 2.3 | criteria-version = 2.3 | accessdate = April 23, 2014
}}GRIN lists the species is native to the following regions: China (Southern), Indian Subcontinent, North Indian Ocean, Indochina.</ref> It bears white to cream-colored flowers on terminal stems.<ref name="magofthai">Nooteboom, H. P. and P. Chalermglin. 2009. The Magnoliaceae of Thailand. Thai Forest Bulletin (Botany) No. 37: 128-129.:</ref> The leaves are [[elliptical]] and get as large as 10 inches long and 3 inches wide. The tree ranges in height of 12–60 feet ''[[in situ#Biology and biomedical engineering|in situ]]''.<ref name="magofthai" />

==Varieties==
''Magnolia liliifera'' was classified as having several [[variety (botany)|varieties]], however these have now been generally accepted as species by several botanists including Hans Peter Nooteboom and Richard B. Figlar according to data compiled by Rafaël Govaerts, a researcher for the [[World Checklist of Selected Plant Families|WCSP]] at Kew Gardens.<ref name="kew">{{Kew list|117679||accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref>

* ''Magnolia liliifera'' var. ''angatensis'' <small>(Blanco) Noot</small>, also accepted as ''Magnolia angatensis'' <small>Blanco</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/namedetail.do?name_id=117443 |title=WCSP |work= World Checklist of Selected Plant Families}}</ref>
* ''Magnolia liliifera'' var. ''beccarii'' <small>(Ridley) Noot.</small>, also accepted as ''Magnolia beccarii'' <small>(Ridl.) ined.</small><ref>{{cite web| url= http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/acceptedRef.do?name_id=351099| title=World Checklist of Selected Plant Families - Magnolia beccarii (Ridl.) ined..}}</ref>
* ''Magnolia liliifera'' var. ''championii'', <small>(Benth.) Pamp</small> also accepted as ''Magnolia championii'' <small>Benth.</small>.<ref name="tropicos">{{cite web| url= http://www.tropicos.org/Name/19300268 | title= Tropicos Name - Magnolia championii Benth. }}</ref>
* ''Magnolia liliifera'' var. ''obovata'' <small>(Korth.)</small>, also accepted as ''[[Magnolia hodgsonii]]'' <small>(Hook.f. & Thom.) H.Keng</small><ref name="efloras">{{cite web| url= http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=2&taxon_id=242351157 | title= Talauma hodgsonii in Flora of China @ www.efloras.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/acceptedRef.do?name_id=117640| title= World Checklist of Selected Plant Families - Magnolia hodgsonii}}</ref> (Note: ''[[Magnolia obovata]]'' is used for a distantly related species from a different [[Section (botany)|section]] of ''Magnolia''.)
* ''Magnolia liliifera'' var. ''singapurensis'' <small>(Ridl.) Govaerts</small>, also accepted as ''Magnolia singapurensis'' <small>(Ridl.) H.Keng</small><ref>{{cite web| title= World Checklist of Selected Plant Families - Magnolia singapurensis | url=http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/namedetail.do?name_id=117832}}</ref>

==Cultivation==
[[File:Magnolia liliifera foliage and flower bud in collage- Provenance of then plant is from Logee's Greenhouse- 2014-05-12 09-40.jpg|thumbnail|right|''Magnolia liliifera'' foliage and flower buds in cultivation.]]
''Magnolia liliifera'' is grown as an [[ornamental plant]] and is suited to culture in pots. Although tropical, the egg magnolia is reported to withstand sub-tropical climates at [[USDA zone]] 10 and higher.<ref name="davesgarden">{{cite web| url= http://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/go/16220 | title= PlantFiles: Egg Magnolia Talauma }}</ref> It has been grown in the West since the Victorian era with the first report of a flowering specimen at Kew Gardens in April, 1862.<ref name="Sargent1895">{{cite book|author=Charles Sprague Sargent|title=Garden and Forest: A Journal of Horticulture, Landscape Art and Forestry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JBM4AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA33|year=1895|publisher=Garden and Forest Publishing Company|pages=33–}}: Referred to as ''Talauma candollei''.</ref> The egg magnolia is valued for its [[fragrant]], egg-like flower which releases a wafting pineapple-like scent in the morning.<ref name="davesgarden" />

